iganshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1240–1275":"1240–1275","0775–0830":"0775–0830","1200–1500":"1200–1500","1237–Female":"1237–Deceased","1250–1320":"1250–1320","1270–1309":"1270–1309","1215–1265":"1215–1265","1214–Female":"1214–Deceased","1275":"1275","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","1214":"1214","1500":"1500","0830":"0830","0775":"0775","Apr 1265":"April 1265","1200":"1200","1265":"1265","1320":"1320","1309":"1309","Gwynnionith, Deheubarth, Wales":"West Wales, Wales","Cardigan Uch Ayron, Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardigan, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Long, Minh, Muoi, Phan, Phat, Vinh, Cuong, Hien, Hoa, Lam, Lan.  Chinese Wing, Chi, Kin, Cheuk, Chi Wai, Chuen, Hon, Keung, Wah, Wai, Chiu, Ho.","Chinese: alternative Mandarin form of the surname 敖, see   Ao  .","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Auerbach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Moshe, Emanuel, Isidor, Bronia, Chaim, Faigy, Menachem, Meyer, Yechezkel.","German: habitational name from any of several places in southern Germany and Austria called Auerbach ‘the stream at the water meadow’. See also 2,   Au  , and   Bach  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from the town of Auerbach in the Upper Palatinate, Bavaria. Compare   Averbach  ."]},{"name":"Ao","meanings":["Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 敖, meaning both ‘rambling’ and ‘deposed king without posthumous titles’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the personal name of <i>Tai Ao</i> (太敖), teacher of the legendary king Zhuanxu (traditional dates: 2514–2437  BC ). (ii) it is said that the surname is also borne by descendants of deposed kings of the former state of Chu, with no posthumous titles, during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC )."]},{"name":"Auer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Hans, Erwin, Matthias, Siegfried, Bernd, Bernhard, Erna, Franz, Fritz, Hermann, Horst.","German (mainly Bavaria): topographic name for someone living by a water meadow, German <i>Au</i>, or a habitational name for someone from a place called Au or Aue (see   Au   and   Aue  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Czechia, and Slovenia."]}]},{"name":"Owain","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Perhaps derived in the Roman period from the Latin name <i>Eugenius</i> (  see  <b>Eugene</b>   ); alternatively, possibly from an Old Celtic name meaning ‘born of Esos’. Esos (or Aesos) was a Celtic god known to have been the subject of a cult in ancient Gaul."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Owain ap Maredudd was born in 1240, his father, Maredudd ab Owain Lord of Ceridigion, was 25 and his mother, Unknown verch Thomas, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Angharad ferch Owain. He died in 1275, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1240–1275":"1240–1275","0775–0830":"0775–0830","1200–1500":"1200–1500","1237–Female":"1237–Surnud","1250–1320":"1250–1320","1270–1309":"1270–1309","1215–1265":"1215–1265","1214–Female":"1214–Surnud","1275":"1275","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","1214":"1214","1500":"1500","0830":"0830","0775":"0775","Apr 1265":"aprill 1265","1200":"1200","1265":"1265","1320":"1320","1309":"1309","Gwynnionith, Deheubarth, Wales":"West Wales, Wales","Cardigan Uch Ayron, Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardigan, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1240–1275":"1240–1275","0775–0830":"0775–0830","1200–1500":"1200–1500","1237–Female":"1237–Kuollut","1250–1320":"1250–1320","1270–1309":"1270–1309","1215–1265":"1215–1265","1214–Female":"1214–Kuollut","1275":"1275","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","1214":"1214","15